Theme comparison

Corey Runkel

10/25/2021

Sean and Corey don’t like ggplot’s defaults

We make a lot of plots in our research, and aim to make even more in the future. So, it’s important that we like what we make. Sean doesn’t like a number of small things that ggplot insists using, such as the grey background. Further, a coherent style can add polish and professionalism to our publications. Corey doesn’t like the ubiquity of the defaults.

Package functions to make our theme easy to use

We have some disagreements on how our theme should look. But we agree that we need one that is easy to use, or we—and especially others who are not as familiar with ggplot and R—won’t use it. This all means that we need to put together a theme of our own, something that a user can call at the end of the ggplot chain. It could also be helpful to suggest some color palettes that fulfill a few requirements, namely accessibility.

We shouldn’t write our own theme from scratch

Luckily, we can build on what professional designers before us have done. And we can be confident in a theme designed professionally by limiting our search to themes that are:

  1. Robust: support the widest set of ggplot functions and normally used plugins (such as scales)
  2. Scaled appropriately: our figures top out around 615 pixels in width

To test these goals, themes will need to render large datasets in our three core geometries—areas, columns, and points—with two text annotations at a size of \(615px \cdot 400px\)

Tests

Last, the column plot from my ECS case:

ecs <- unzip(zipfile = "../../bbel/EU GFC/data/tops.zip", files = "output/newstaging/tops.csv") %>% #unzip file downloaded from link above
  read_csv(guess_max = 2500) %>%
  rename_with(~ str_remove(.x, "t_"), t_class:t_is_canceled) %>% #remove t_ leading each variable
  select(class:ref, procedure, allot_dt, settlement_dt:auction_type, intended_volume, marginal_rate, allotment_at_marginal_rate, alloted_amount, weighted_average_rate, bid_amount, number_of_bidders, min_rate_bids, max_rate_bids) %>% #remove irrelevant columns
  mutate_at(vars(class, procedure, auction_type), as_factor) %>% #change three character variables to factors
  mutate(term = fct_relevel(case_when(class == "LTRO" & duration < 81 ~ "STRO",
                          class == "LTRO" & duration %in% 82:110 ~ "3 month",
                          class == "LTRO" & duration %in% 170:190 ~ "6 month",
                          class == "LTRO" & duration %in% 190:400 ~ "1 year"), "1 year", "STRO", "6 month", "3 month")) %>%
  filter(!is.na(settlement_dt)) %>% #remove OMOs that never settled
      filter(class == "LTRO", between(settlement_dt, as_date("2007-08-24"), as_date("2010-04-01"))) %>%
      mutate(outstanding = if_else(alloted_amount > bid_amount, bid_amount, alloted_amount), date = settlement_dt) %>%
      select(ref, settlement_dt, maturity_dt, date, outstanding, term, marginal_rate) %>%
      group_by(ref, term, settlement_dt, maturity_dt, marginal_rate) %>%
      complete(date = seq.Date(date, maturity_dt-1, by = "day")) %>%
      fill(outstanding) %>%
      ungroup() %>%
#PLOT STARTS HERE#
  ggplot() +
  geom_rect(aes(xmin = as_date("2008-10-15"), xmax = as_date("2010-12-31"), ymin = -Inf, ymax = Inf), fill = "#4a4a4a", alpha = .002) +
  geom_col(aes(date, outstanding/1000, fill = term), alpha = .5) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::dollar_format(prefix = "€")) +
  scale_x_date(date_labels = "%b %Y") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = wesanderson::wes_palette("Chevalier1", n = 4, type = "discrete")) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = "Outstanding SLTROs (billions)")
